Float flying in Alaska sometimes requires hauling external loads such as ATVs, boats, or lumber to get the job done.  Special pilot training, a certain level of flying experience, and a few extra procedures are required. Of utmost importance are plenty of good ratchet straps and some solid attach points on the cargo and the float struts. As you might have guessed, strapping an ATV on the outside of a floatplane has a detrimental effect on performance, to say the least.

Yesterday I had the once in a lifetime opportunity of flying the Navajo as photo ship for the Eielson AFB F-35s (Glock 1 and 2) as well as F-16s (MiG 1 and 2) around Denali. I was busy flying and radio relaying formation instructions from the photographers in the back. The Navajo isn't the quickest aircraft so they had to hang in there, and did an incredible job. All I got myself was what my 360 cam picked up, but the photographers absolutely crushed it! 

Check them out when they're posted on aviation-photocrew.com and airtoair.at
.
.
.
.
.

Practice tight step turns enough and eventually you'll find the limit! Easy enough to recognize and correct as seen here, the outboard float begins digging in under high centrifugal force. The tightest step turns require a perfect balance of speed and power for the turn radius desired, here I didn't have enough speed entering the turn. Constantly learning is only part of the fun of flying floats!
